Prioritize issuance of demand letters to all accountable officers especially those with cash advances that has been outstanding for more than one year;
Impose withholding of salary and the application of other sanctions as provided under paragraphs 9.2 and 9.3 of COA Circular 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 to all active employees or still connected with the municipal government;
Require retiring accountable official or employee, if there is any, to undertake an authorization (in affidavit form) to deduct financial obligations including unliquidated cash advances from the terminal leave benefits pursuant to 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012.
Assign personnel from the Accounting Office who will closely monitor the movement of the long outstanding cash advances and to prepare quarterly report copy furnished the Audit Team.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Create an Inventory Committee composed of representatives from the Mayor’s Office, the GSO and the Accounting Office to undertake the physical count of PPE as soon as possible to determine the existence of these properties, whereabouts and their actual condition pursuant to Section 124 of MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I;

Require the Committee to submit the RPCPPE as soon as the conduct of inventory is completed; 

Require the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer (GSO) – Designate to undertake a regular reconciliation of their records on PPE in order to have a fair presentation of the PPE accounts in the financial statements; and


Assign additional personnel to the GSO to address the problem on lack of manpower.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor and the Municipal Accountant:
1. Enforce immediate settlement of long outstanding cash advances totaling  ₱748,784.00 pursuant to COA Circular Nos. 97-02 and COA Circular No. 2012-004 dated February 10, 1997 and November 28, 2012, respectively;
2. Prioritize issuance of demand letters to all accountable officers especially those cash advances that has been outstanding for more than a year;
3. Impose the withholding of salary and the institution of other sanctions as provided under paragraphs 9.2 and 9.3 of COA Circular 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
4. Ensure that no additional cash advances be granted to those officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances pursuant to the provisions of Section 89 of P.D. 1445 and Item 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
5. Require retiring accountable official or employee to undertake an authorization (in affidavit form) to deduct financial obligations including unliquidated cash advances from the terminal leave benefits pursuant to 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;
6. Assign personnel from the Accounting Office who will closely monitor the movement of the long cash advances and to prepare quarterly report copy furnished the Audit Team.

We recommended that:

1. The Municipal Treasurer cause the immediate submission of all CY 2017  DVs and supporting documents not yet submitted to the Accounting Office so that the latter could submit the same to the Audit Team;

2. Hereafter, the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer ensure that DVs are supported with necessary documents before certifying the disbursements and releasing the checks, respectively pursuant to Section 38 (2) and 41 of the Manual on New Government Accounting System (MNGAS) for LGUs, Volume I;

3. The Municipal Accountant strictly adhere to the existing regulation to submit DVs and supporting documents within the reglementary period pursuant to Sections 7.2 and 7.3 of COA Circular No. 94-006 dated February 17, 1994 and Section 7.2.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-006 dated September 15, 2009; and
4. It was also emphasized that failure to submit the foregoing reports may cause the automatic suspension of salaries and such other liabilities and penalties as provided in Sections 39, 41, and 122 of P.D. 1445, Section 23 of the Administrative Code of 1987 and Article 218 of the Revised Penal Code.

